<h1>What is a problem?</h1>

<p>
A problem can be defined as
<em>a difference between things as perceived and things as desired</em>.&nbsp;
In RE we are primarily concerned with identifying the problem.&nbsp;
We aren't looking for a solution (that's the role of design);
we are defining the problem a solution would solve,
and finding criteria to identify a successful solution.&nbsp;
</p>


<h1>Starting points</h1>

<p>
Sometimes it's hard to get started.&nbsp;
One approach is to use an easy but less-than-ideal starting point,
and then work on it until you have a problem definition
that matches the template above.&nbsp;
</p>

<ol>
  <li>  Start with a potential solution (then ask what problems it solves).&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  Start with a technology (then ask what someone would really, really
          want that for).&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  Start with a <a href='glossaryExternal.html#simile'>simile</a>
          (then ask questions to find out
          how a solution would be like that).&nbsp;
          <br/><i>[Simile:&nbsp; Oxford is like a hive of industry.]</i>
  </li>
  <li>  Start with a <a href='glossaryExternal.html#metaphor'>metaphor</a>
          (then ask questions to find out
          how a solution would different from that).&nbsp;
          <br/><i>[Metaphor:&nbsp; Oxford is a hive of industry.]</i>
  </li>
  <li>  Start with a mockup;  a mockup is a reified metaphor.&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  Start with a name;  make up one if necessary.
          But be aware of what connotations it carries;
          connotations are the strength of using a name,
          but also the weakness.&nbsp;
          Then talk about a solution using the name.&nbsp;
  </li>
</ol>

<p>
<i>By the time you realize a project has begun,
the beginning phase is already past.</i>&nbsp;
The moment you realize you are starting to develop something,
stop and write down everything you can remember
that led up to this point.&nbsp;
It is during this unconscious initial phase
that the biggest assumptions are made.&nbsp;
</p>

<h1>Context-free process questions</h1>
<ol>
  <li>  Who is the client for a solution to this problem?&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  What is a successful solution worth to this client?&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  (If implausible)
          What is the real reason for wanting to solve this problem?&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  Who should be on the requirements team?&nbsp;
          Should there be a single team or more than one?&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  How much time do we have to do this?&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  What is the tradeoff between the time it takes and
          the value of the result?&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  Can we copy something that already exists?&nbsp;
  </li>
</ol>

<h1>Context-free solution questions</h1>
<ol>
  <li>  What problems does this solution solve?&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  What problems could this solution create?&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  What environment is this solution likely to encounter?&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  Is there someplace I can go see where a solution will be used?&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  What kind of precision or reliability is required or desired in a solution?&nbsp;
  </li>
</ol>

<h1>Metaquestions about questioning</h1>
<ol>
  <li>  "Am I asking you too many questions?"&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  "Do my questions seem relevant?"&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  "Are you the right person to answer these questions?"&nbsp;
          Are your answers official?"&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  "In order to be sure we understand each other,
          I've found that it helps me to have things in writing
          so I can study them at leisure.
          May I write down your answers and give you a written copy
          to study and approve?"&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  "The written material has been helpful,
          but I find I understand some things better
          if I can discuss them face to face.&nbsp;
          Can we get together at some point,
          so we can know each other better
          and clarify some of these points?"&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  "Is there anyone else who can give me useful answers?"&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  "Is there anything else I should be asking you?"&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  "Is there anything you want to ask me?"&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li>  "May I return or call you later with more questions,
          in case I don't cover everything this time?"&nbsp;
  </li>
</ol>


<h1>Effective listening</h1>

<p class='i'>
"People are given two ears but only one mouth,
because listening is twice as hard as talking."
</p>

<ul>
  <li> Pay attention.
  </li>
  <li> Look at the person who is speaking.
  </li>
  <li> Don't interrupt.
  </li>
  <li> Hear the specific words the person is speaking,
       not just the overall meaning.
  </li>
</ul>

<p>
Consider these items which can affect the success (or not) of your elicitation:&nbsp;
</p>

<ol>
  <li> What is your attitude?
    <ul>
      <li> Are you experienced or a novice with this area?
      </li>
      <li> Do you like/respect/trust the speaker, or not?
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li> What is the speaker's attitude and situation?
    <ul>
      <li> Relaxed/nervous/impatient/confident/...?
      </li>
      <li> Knowledgeable or not?
      </li>
      <li> Motivated to give you what you need, or not?&nbsp; If not, why not?
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li> What is the space like?
    <ul>
      <li> Your office, his/her office, a neutral location?&nbsp;
        Each has advantages.&nbsp;
      </li>
      <li> Quiet or noisy?&nbsp; Usually quiet is much better.&nbsp;
      </li>
      <li> Private or public?&nbsp; Again, each has advantages.&nbsp;
      </li>
      <li> Useful materials (charts, notes, reference books, ...)
        are nearby or not?
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ol>


<h1>Active listening</h1>

<p>
Whatever your questions, the process of asking them will be more efficient
if you practice <i>active listening</i>:&nbsp;
</p>

<ul>
  <li> Indicate you are listening (nod your head, say "uh-huh" or
       "I understand" if you in fact understand &mdash;
       this doesn't mean you agree, merely that you understand).&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li> If you don't understand, let the person know.&nbsp; Be specific.&nbsp;
  </li>
  <li> Every so often, paraphrase what they have said
       ("If I understand correctly, you are saying that ...").&nbsp;
  </li>
</ul>

<p>
Paraphrasing what you are hearing is effective because
</p>

<ol>
  <li> it shows the speaker that you are interested and paying attention
  </li>
  <li> it helps the two of you identify misunderstandings and miscommunications
  </li>
  <li> it gives an opportunity for the speaker to correct any misunderstandings
  </li>
  <li> it gives you confirmation that you have understood (when you have).
  </li>
</ol>



<h1 class='i'>Acknowledgements</h1>

<p> Parts were adapted from Gause and Weinberg,
<i>Exploring requirements: Quality before design</i>.&nbsp;
</p>


